.\" Man page for reticulate(1)
.\" Generated from CLI and grammar documentation.
.TH RETICULATE 1 "2026-03-06" "reticulate 0.1.0" "Session Type Tools"
.
.SH NAME
reticulate \- session type analyzer: parse, build state space, check lattice properties
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B reticulate
.RI [ OPTIONS ]
.I TYPE_STRING
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B reticulate
parses a session type expression, constructs its labelled transition system
(state space), and checks whether the resulting poset forms a lattice.
.PP
A session type describes a communication protocol on an object \(em the
permitted sequences of method calls, branches, and selections.
The state space of a session type, ordered by reachability, forms a poset.
.B reticulate
verifies the lattice properties of this poset: existence of top and bottom
elements, and pairwise meets and joins for all states.
.PP
The tool supports three output modes: a text summary (default), Graphviz DOT
source, and rendered Hasse diagrams.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I TYPE_STRING
Session type expression to analyze (required).  Must be quoted in the shell
to protect special characters.
.TP
.B \-\-dot
Print the Hasse diagram as Graphviz DOT source to stdout.  Does not require
the
.B graphviz
Python package.  Mutually exclusive with
.BR \-\-hasse .
.TP
.BI \-\-hasse " [PATH]"
Render the Hasse diagram to
.I PATH
(default:
.BR hasse_output ).
Requires both the
.B graphviz
Python package and the system
.B dot
binary.
.TP
.BI \-\-fmt " FORMAT"
Output format for
.BR \-\-hasse .
One of:
.BR png ,
.BR svg ,
.BR pdf ,
.BR dot .
Default:
.BR png .
.TP
.B \-\-no\-labels
Hide state labels on nodes (show numeric IDs only).
.TP
.B \-\-no\-edge\-labels
Hide transition labels on edges.
.TP
.BI \-\-title " TITLE"
Set a title for the Hasse diagram.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help message and exit.
.
.SH GRAMMAR
The session type grammar accepted by
.B reticulate
is a core grammar with 9 constructs and no desugaring:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
S  ::=  &{ m1 : S1 , ... , mn : Sn }    branch (external choice)
     |  +{ l1 : S1 , ... , ln : Sn }    selection (internal choice)
     |  S1 || S2                         parallel composition
     |  S1 . S2                          continuation (after parallel)
     |  rec X . S                        recursion
     |  ( S )                            grouping
     |  X                                type variable
     |  wait                             parallel branch completed
     |  end                              session terminated
.fi
.RE
.PP
Every construct has exactly one meaning.  There are no desugaring rules.
.
.SS Precedence
.B .
(continuation) binds tighter than
.B ||
(parallel).  Use parentheses to override:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
&{a: end} || &{b: end}       parses as   &{a: end} || &{b: end}
(&{a: wait} || &{b: wait}) . &{c: end}   continuation after parallel
.fi
.RE
.PP
The body of
.B rec X . S
is parsed at atom level (self-delimiting constructs only), so
.B rec X . &{...}
works as expected.
.
.SS end vs wait
.B end
signals final session termination.  Nothing may follow it.
.PP
.B wait
signals that a parallel branch has completed and is ready to synchronise.
It is used inside parallel branches that are followed by a continuation:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
(&{read: wait} || &{write: wait}) . &{close: end}
.fi
.RE
.PP
After both branches reach
.BR wait ,
the continuation
.B &{close: end}
executes.
.
.SS Continuation
The
.B .
operator chains a continuation after a parallel composition.
The left operand is typically a
.B Parallel
node (possibly parenthesised).  This is the only construct that requires
shared post-synchronisation.  7 of the 34 benchmark protocols use this
pattern.
.
.SS Unicode support
The parser accepts Unicode alternatives for common operators:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
\[u2295]   \(->   +    (selection)
\[u2225]   \(->   ||   (parallel)
\[u03BC]   \(->   rec  (recursion)
.fi
.RE
.
.SH CONSTRUCTORS
.TP
.B &{ m1 : S1 , ... , mn : Sn }
.I Branch
(external choice).  The environment chooses which method to call.
Each
.I mi
is a method name and
.I Si
is its continuation type.
.TP
.B +{ l1 : S1 , ... , ln : Sn }
.I Selection
(internal choice).  The object decides which branch to take.
Each
.I li
is a label and
.I Si
is the continuation.
.TP
.B S1 || S2
.I Parallel
composition.  Two concurrent execution paths on a shared object.
The product construction
.I L(S1) \(mu L(S2)
produces a componentwise-ordered lattice.
This is the key novelty that makes lattice structure
.I necessary
rather than merely nice.
.TP
.B S1 . S2
.I Continuation
after parallel.  Chains a post-synchronisation protocol after a
parallel block completes.
.TP
.B rec X . S
.I Recursion.
Binds variable
.I X
in body
.IR S .
The state space contains cycles; lattice checking quotients by
strongly connected components.
.TP
.B wait
.I Synchronisation point.
A parallel branch has completed.  Used inside parallel branches
followed by a continuation.
.TP
.B end
.I Terminated
session.  No further method calls are permitted.  Final.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful analysis.
.TP
.B 1
Parse error or state-space construction error.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Analyze a simple protocol:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate '&{open: &{read: end, close: end}}'
Session type: &{open: &{read: end, close: end}}
States: 3  |  Transitions: 3  |  SCCs: 3

Lattice check: \[u2713] IS a lattice
  Top reachable:    \[u2713]
  Bottom reachable: \[u2713]
  All meets exist:  \[u2713]
  All joins exist:  \[u2713]
.fi
.RE
.PP
Parallel composition:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate '&{read: end} || &{write: end}'
Session type: &{read: end} || &{write: end}
States: 4  |  Transitions: 4  |  SCCs: 4

Lattice check: \[u2713] IS a lattice
.fi
.RE
.PP
Parallel with continuation (using wait):
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate '(&{read: wait} || &{write: wait}) . &{close: end}'
.fi
.RE
.PP
Generate DOT output and pipe to Graphviz:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate \-\-dot '&{a: end, b: end}' | dot \-Tpng \-o out.png
.fi
.RE
.PP
Render a Hasse diagram directly:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate \-\-hasse diagram \-\-fmt svg '&{a: end, b: end}'
Rendered to diagram.svg
.fi
.RE
.PP
Recursive protocol with parallel:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ reticulate 'rec X . &{call: X, done: end} || rec Y . &{ping: Y, stop: end}'
.fi
.RE
.
.SH PYTHON API
.B reticulate
can also be used as a Python library:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
from reticulatep import parse, build_statespace, check_lattice

ast = parse("&{a: end, b: end}")
ss = build_statespace(ast)
result = check_lattice(ss)
print(result.is_lattice)   # True
.fi
.RE
.PP
See the full API in the
.I USER\-MANUAL.md
shipped with the package.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I reticulate/parser.py
Tokenizer, recursive-descent parser, pretty-printer.
.TP
.I reticulate/statespace.py
State-space construction (labelled transition system).
.TP
.I reticulate/lattice.py
Lattice property checking (SCC quotient, meets, joins).
.TP
.I reticulate/product.py
Product construction for parallel composition.
.TP
.I reticulate/termination.py
Termination and well-formedness checking.
.TP
.I reticulate/morphism.py
Morphism hierarchy (isomorphism, embedding, projection, Galois connection).
.TP
.I reticulate/visualize.py
Hasse diagram generation (DOT / Graphviz).
.TP
.I reticulate/testgen.py
Test generation from session type state spaces.
.
